###This analysis is an *a priori* DGE analysis in edgeR of hormone and hormone receptor genes to determine if this subset of genes is differentially expressed by WET and DRY treatments:
-

**1) First I searched Ensembl for Mus Musculus sequences for genes important for male rodent reproduction that are likely to be present in testes of P. eremicus.**


***This is Ensembl release 88 March 2017***

I downloaded the gene sequences for each gene of interest.



**2) Then I searched for these sequences (each sequence was a separate query) as a BLASTn search within a database I made of my P. eremicus transcriptome.**

The P. eremicus transcriptome datatbase was made as shown below:

	makeblastdb -in /mnt/data3/lauren/LHsearch/db/good.BINPACKER.cdhit.fasta -out TESTEScds -dbtype nucl


Each BLASTn search yielded a single P. eremicus transcriptome contig ID result (eg. BINPACKER.134.8).

**3) I then retrieved each of these P. eremicus transcriptome contigs (the nucleotide sequence for each ID), and I did a BLASTn search of the sequence on the web platform of NCBI BLAST in order to confirm that the P. eremicus sequence corresponded to the Mus Musculus gene of interest.**
	
For example: confirming that the Mus Star gene which matched my P. eremiucs contig ID (BINPACKER.134.8) nucleotide sequence was actually matching to the Star gene on a BLASTn search: 
(BLASTn Database nucleotide collection (nr/nt); BLASTn optimized for highly similar sequences (megablast)).

Those BLASTn results which had a correspondance for the same gene in Peromyscus eremicus as Mus musculus were considered good matches, and then I could proceed with those P. eremicus Contig IDs for these reproductive genes (14 genes). 


**4) I cross-referenced those contig IDs in my matrix table, which shows each P. eremicus contig ID match to the ensembl gene ID for Mus, in order to get the ensembl gene IDs:**

The matrix file is here:

lauren@davinci:/mnt/data3/lauren/TESTESdge/MUS/NEWESTfinalMUS.txt


For example, I can search for BINPACKER.134.8:

	grep "BINPACKER.134.8" NEWESTFinalMUS.txt

RESULT:

BINPACKER.134.8	ENSMUSG00000031574.8

Thus, ENSMUSG00000031574.8 matches to the contig ID BINPACKER.134.8, and I can again confirm that this is a gene match for Star by looking in ensembl, which it is:

Gene: Star ENSMUSG00000031574

**5) Next I searched for these 9 ensembl gene IDs (e.g.  ENSMUSG00000031574.8) in my edgeR DGE dataset:**


Specifically, I determined the relative CPM values of the WET vs. DRY treatment groups for these Ensembl IDs that corresponded to these reproductive genes of interest in order to determine if they were differentially expressed by treatment. 

I only conducted this a priori test for DGE for 9 Ensembl gene IDs, so this a priori test does not need to be adjusted as rigorously for multiple comparisons as the transcriptome-wide analysis.  Rather the p-value needs to be adjusted for 9 comparisons.

**I retrieved this DGE data from the edgeR DGE analysis:**

	tag.name<-c("Star", "Prlr", "Lhgcr", "Inha", "Ghrl", "Esrrg", "Esrra", "Ar", "Acvr2a")
	tag.keep<-c("ENSMUSG00000031574.8","ENSMUSG00000005268.20", "ENSMUSG00000024107.6",
            "ENSMUSG00000032968.4", "ENSMUSG00000064177.8", "ENSMUSG00000026610.13",
            "ENSMUSG00000024955.13", "ENSMUSG00000046532.7", "ENSMUSG00000052155.5")

	group.dif<-cpm(b)
	group.dif<-group.dif[tag.keep,]
	colnames(group.dif)<-group
	group.dif<-melt(group.dif)
	names(group.dif)<-c("ID","group","cpm")
	group.dif$group[group.dif$group==1]<-"WET"
	group.dif$group[group.dif$group==2]<-"DRY"
	par(mfrow=c(3,3))
	for(i in 1:length(tag.keep)){
  		boxplot(cpm~group,group.dif[group.dif$ID==tag.keep[i],],
          main=tag.name[i],cex.main=2,
          ylab="count (cpm)",frame.plot=F,col=(c("brown","light blue")))
  
	}

	et$table[tag.keep,]
